{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652014"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:31:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:31:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18505"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18505"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.23,0.55,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11234"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76759"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11234"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18505"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62252"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"6960"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26057"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26323"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76759"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hepatic portal vein delivers blood from the digestive organs and spleen to the liver. Understanding its formation and tributaries is essential for understanding portal circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the formation of the hepatic portal vein?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superior mesenteric vein joins inferior mesenteric vein","Right and left portal veins unite","Inferior mesenteric vein joins superior mesenteric vein","Superior mesenteric vein joins splenic vein","Right and left gastric veins unite"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hepatic portal vein is formed when the \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior mesenteric vein joins splenic vein\u003C/strong\u003E behind the neck of the pancreas. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior mesenteric vein joins superior mesenteric vein\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it typically drains into the splenic vein. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eright and left gastric veins unite\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as these are smaller tributaries that drain into the portal vein separately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eright and left portal veins unite\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as these are terminal branches of the hepatic portal vein within the liver, not vessels that form it. The suggestion that the \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior mesenteric vein joins inferior mesenteric vein\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this is not the normal anatomical arrangement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe hepatic portal vein is approximately 8 cm long and carries about 75% of the liver\u0027s blood supply. This venous blood is rich in nutrients absorbed from the gastrointestinal tract and requires hepatic processing before entering the systemic circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The hepatic portal vein is formed by the union of the superior mesenteric vein and splenic vein behind the neck of the pancreas.","The inferior mesenteric vein typically joins the splenic vein before it unites with the superior mesenteric vein.","The hepatic portal vein carries nutrient-rich blood from the gastrointestinal tract and spleen to the liver, comprising about 75% of hepatic blood supply."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62252"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18505"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62252"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T08:12:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T08:13:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11234"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76759"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i